SIMPLE: quip
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Quip
<hw>Quip</hw> <pr>(kw⟦icr⟧p)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. W.
<ets>chwip</ets> a quick flirt or turn, <ets>chwipio</ets> to whip, to
move briskly, and E. <ets>whip</ets>. Cf. <er>Quib</er>,
<er>Quibble</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A smart, sarcastic turn or
jest; a taunt; a severe retort; a gibe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Quips</qex>, and cranks, and wanton wiles.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was full of joke and jest,⟦br⟧
But all his merry <qex>quips</qex> are o'er.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A short humorous or witty comment or observation,
usually spontaneously formed in response to a prior comment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Quip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Quip
<hw>Quip</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Quipped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Quipping</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To taunt; to treat
with quips.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The more he laughs, and does her closely <qex>quip</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Quip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Quip
<hw>Quip</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To scoff; to use taunts.</def>
<rj><au>Sir H. Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Quipo</ent>⟦br⟧
